ns between states, and he asserted that this disentanglement required transitioning to a planned and largely self-sufficient national economy, made possible by a radical monetary policy. Fichte's ideas have resurfaced with nearly every crisis of globalization from the Napoleonic wars to the present, and his book remains a uniquely systematic and complete discussion of what John Maynard Keynes later termed "national self-sufficiency." Fichte's provocative contribution to the social contract tradition reminds us, Nakhimovsky concludes, that the combination of a liberal theory of the state with an open economy and international system is a much more contingent and precarious outcome than many recent theorists have tended to assume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCommercial policyxHistoryx18th century. 0aCommercial policyxHistoryy18th century. 0aRepublicanismxHistoryx18th century. 0aRepublicanismxHistoryy18th century. 0aSocial contractxHistoryx18th century. 0aSocial contractxHistoryy18th century. 0aState, ThexHistoryx18th century. 0aState, ThexHistoryy18th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aClosed Commercial State.  aEmmanuel-Joseph Sieys.  aEuropean states system.  aFrench Revolution.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJohann Gottlieb Fichte.  aPerpetual Peace.  aRousseau.  aThe Closed Commercial State.  acommerce.  aconstitutional politics.  aconstitutional theory.  aconstitutionalism.  adivision of labor.  aeconomic relations.  aequality.  afinance.  aglobal trade.  aindividual liberty.  ainternational relations.  amarket society.  amodern finance.  amonetary policy.  amonetary system.  anational economy.  anational self-sufficiency.  apeace.  aperpetual peace.  aplanned economy.